The European « Green Deal »
NEW YORK – Europe has done it.
The « European Green Pact » announced by the European Commission is to date the first comprehensive sustainable development plan decided by a large region of the planet.
It thus becomes a landmark for the entire world – a guide for the transformation towards a prosperous, socially inclusive, and ecologically sustainable economy, a first agenda, for everyone, to achieve this.
Of course, the task awaiting Europeans is impressive.
Even reading the documents that have just been made public is daunting: a flood at first glance of plans, consultations, regulatory frameworks, laws, budgets, and diplomacy, a large number of involved and related subjects, ranging from energy to transport, from food to industry.
Its detractors will mock European bureaucracy.
But it is a bureaucracy in the best Weberian sense of the term: it is rational.
The sustainable development goals are clearly stated, the targets are defined according to objectives set within a schedule, and the programs and procedures are adapted to the targets.
Overall, the stated ambition is to achieve « carbon neutrality » (net zero emissions of greenhouse gases) by 2050, to set up a circular economy that ends the destructive pollution caused by plastics and other petrochemical derivatives, pesticides, and toxic waste, to establish a « farm to table » food system that does not kill people by making them eat products overly processed by industry, nor does it kill the earth through unsustainable agricultural practices.
And the European Commission understands that the method to achieve this must rely on the citizens themselves.
Again, detractors will view the announcements of public consultations as empty talk for dreamers.
But go tell the president of France, Emmanuel Macron, who has faced more than a year of demonstrations turning into riots, or the president of Chile, Sebastián Piñera, whose country suddenly rose up this autumn after a slight increase in metro ticket prices, that these are useless conversations.
Macron and Piñera are both convinced of the necessity of ecological change.
Both have committed to achieving carbon neutrality in their countries by 2050.
And both are desperately trying to figure out how to organize or structure a public consultation, but afterwards.
American proponents of neoliberalism will again mock and claim that the « market » will know how to address climate change.
But one only needs to look at today's United States.
If neoliberalism treats the planet as it has treated American infrastructure, we all have cause for concern.
Arriving at an airport in the United States means having to endure elevators, escalators, broken shuttles, taxis that don't arrive, non-existent rail connections, highways whose lanes are in such poor condition that you can't drive on them, replaced by detours.
The reason for these breakdowns is simple: corruption.
Each American election cycle now costs 8 billion dollars, or more, and is funded by billionaires, major oil companies, the military-industrial complex, the healthcare industry lobby, and interest groups determined to lower taxes and protect the status quo at all costs.
The solutions offered by the market are a farce when politics is subject to all the influences emanating from it, as is the case in the United States.
The European Green Pact shows what a government should be like, and not a government subordinate to the interests of businesses.
The European Green Deal in fact demonstrates the success of European social democracy (in its operational sense and not strictly partisan).
A mixed economy, which combines markets, the regulatory power of the state, the public sector, and civil society, will pursue a mixed strategy: public objectives, public investments in infrastructure, private investments in industrial transformation, research and development missions based on public-private partnerships, and an informed population.
In fact, it is an industrial policy at its most sophisticated level.
(I recently outlined, in broad terms, what a social-democratic Green New Deal strategy would look like for the United States.)
We have reasons to be optimistic.
The most important point is that the advanced technologies that will allow the creation of an advanced, decarbonized, resource-efficient, and therefore ecologically sustainable economy already exist at the commercial or pre-commercial stage.
By combining renewable energy, digital technologies, advanced materials, and collaborative economy in transportation or other infrastructures, we can decarbonize the energy system, move toward a circular economy, and drastically reduce the flow of primary resources.
But this requires overcoming three major challenges.
The first is to overcome the interests seeking to maintain the status quo.
The major oil companies will have to absorb the losses, but workers in the sector and mining regions should receive compensation in the form of income support, retraining through education, and other public aids.
The European plan rightly claims a « just transition ».
The second challenge is that of financing.
Europe, like all other regions of the world, will have to redirect a relatively small part of its production, from 1% to 2%, towards the green economy, particularly concerning new infrastructure, public markets, research and development, the renewal of industrial equipment, etc. The funding will come from the private sector, but also from public budgets.
Europe must stand up to the ideologues opposed to an increase in EU spending.
Facts must be taken into account.
The last major challenge is diplomatic.
Europe represents about 9.1% of global carbon dioxide emissions, while China's share rises to 30% and that of the United States to 14%.
Even if Europe succeeds in implementing its Green Pact in its entirety, it will be in vain if other regions of the world do not join it in its struggle.
European leaders therefore rightly consider diplomacy to be fundamental to the success of the Green Pact.
Let us take the example of China.
After decades of rapid growth, which eliminated mass poverty, China has become the world's leading emitter of CO2 (although its emissions per capita remain two times lower than those of the United States).
China alone will determine the future of the global climate.
On the one hand, Chinese leaders know that their country is extremely vulnerable to climate change and risks diplomatic isolation if it does not make sufficient efforts to decarbonize; on the other hand, they must face the dangers of the unfortunate cold war launched by America.
Hardliners within the government and Chinese coal lobbies resist decarbonization, especially since Trump himself rejects it, under pressure from the United States.
European diplomacy can make a difference if it refuses to subscribe to America's insidious measures to hinder China and instead proposes a positive and unambiguous partnership to the latter: working together to establish sustainable infrastructure, development, and technology in Eurasia, within the framework of a Chinese Green Deal comparable to Europe's.
Such a partnership would be of immense benefit to Europe, China, and the dozen Eurasian countries that lie between them, not to mention the world as a whole.
Europe has taken a historic step with its ambitious, mobilizing, and achievable plan.
The Green Deal is a powerful signal of hope in a world of uncertainties and instability.
